Expansins promote the elimination of hydrogen bonds between cellulose and hemicellulose fibers, and indirectly the degradation of pectins by increasing access to pectin remodeling enzymes (
 Cosgrove, 2000; 
 Wang et al., 2018). In avocados, expansins are poorly understood, showing a little detection in ripen avocadoes (
 Rose et al., 2000). Likewise, cellulase activity has been widely studied in avocados. Similarly, to pectin-degrading enzymes, cellulase detection and activity increase during avocado softening, changing the elastic properties of cellulose matrix (
 Pesis et al., 1978; 
 Sakurai and Nevins, 1997; 
 Jeong et al., 2002; 
 Jeong and Huber, 2004).
